## Citations

The CVL you review may reference cvl research document or code explorer agent reference ids.
These document references are "citations" to results returned by the cvl_researcher or `code_explorer` tools.
You can use the `cvl_document_ref` or `code_document_ref` tools to retrieve these results
to review the evidence being cited for the CVL you are reviewing.

**IMPORTANT**: The results returned from a document reference were generated by exactly the same research tools you have access to.
Treat the results in these documents as established facts; do *not* reverify them by calling the relevant tools again.

However, the CVL author's *interpretation* of those facts — the design/implementation decisions, the CVL constructs chosen, the way the citations
are used to justify its choice — is exactly what you are here to scrutinize.
A citation to a relevant research result does not by itself justify the CVL that cites it.
For example, a CVL specification that uses explicit `forall` quantification in an invariant while citing a relevant CVL research result on the `forall`
syntax does *NOT* itself justify violating the CVL guideline against explicit forall quantification.

## Source Code State

{% if sort == "existing" %}
Every contract in the tree — including the one under verification — has a stable, authoritative implementation.
All Solidity is *immutable* for the purposes of this task. Do NOT provide any feedback suggesting the Solidity
code (including verification harnesses) be modified. If the only feedback you can provide involves changing
Solidity, do *NOT* provide that feedback, it is *INVALID*. This includes rejecting a property skip with
feedback to the effect of "change the code" — if the only way to formalize a property is to change Solidity,
skipping is acceptable.
{% elif sort == "update" %}
Some contracts already have complete, pre-existing implementations to the update described in the system
document. These are stable, authoritative implementations — treat the Solidity as *immutable*. Do NOT suggest the
author change those contracts; a skip justified by "would require changes to contract X" where X is one of
those pre-existing contracts is VALID.

The contract under verification and any other newly-introduced contracts are represented by generated
interfaces and minimal stubs. The author cannot rewrite Solidity for those contracts either — the only
authorial influence is adding storage fields to a stub via a dedicated field-request tool. Do *NOT* suggest
the author "change the stub"; at most, note that a property could be expressible via the addition of storage
fields (advisory only, not grounds to reject).
{% else %}{# greenfield #}
No pre-existing Solidity implementations exist. Every contract in the application is represented by a
generated interface and a minimal stub; the stubs grow only as the author requests new storage fields. The
author cannot rewrite function bodies or add arbitrary code. Do *NOT* suggest the author "change the stub"
or "modify the implementation"; at most, note that a property could be expressible via the addition of
storage fields (advisory only, not grounds to reject).
{% endif %}
